<h1>Engagements</h1>

<p class="lede">Run the practice against your codebase, or alongside your team.
Architectural authority stays with you. The work arrives as verified, recorded, reviewable
steps.</p>

<p class="bio">Andrew T. Marcus—systems architect (MIT M.Arch). He developed the Ho System
and has shipped more than ten production systems with it—including <a
href="https://sageframe.substack.com/p/ho-process-methodology">Kanyō, a computer-vision
system running at Harvard</a>, built without knowing how to code. He writes about human–AI
collaboration at <a href="https://sageframe.substack.com">sageframe.substack.com</a>.</p>

<h2>Evidence, not adjectives</h2>
<p><strong>Kanyō</strong>—a production computer-vision system built by a non-developer in
six weeks, monitoring falcon cameras at Harvard, still running. <strong>The supacode
contribution</strong>—disciplined work inside <em>someone else's</em> repository: PR
discipline, host-convention matching, and a wrong assumption corrected on the record rather
than papered over. That last one is the point: the practice's answer to “what is it like when
this touches our code” is a visible, honest record.</p>

<h2>Two shapes</h2>
<p>Brought to your codebase—the practice run against your real project, with you in the
room. Or taught to your team—the discipline itself transferred: your environment encoded,
your vocabulary built, your first {% term "arcs", "arc" %} walked together. Both share one
front door.</p>

<h2>What you receive</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The working record—the sidecar ho-process: every step, its plan, and its look-back.</li>
  <li>The environment encoding—CLAUDE.md, the verification stack, your conventions made explicit.</li>
  <li>Optionally, a tool layer that makes the practice's mechanics available to your agent sessions, installed and configured.</li>
  <li>The discipline itself, transferred to your sessions.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The line</h2>
<p>The methodology is open—all of it is on this site. The facilitation judgment is the
engagement. That is the whole paywall, stated plainly.</p>

